;; cli-assist-full profile: clojure-mcp's structural editing + smart reader
;; brought back as FIRST-CLASS tools, for use alongside a CLI assistant
;; (e.g. Claude Code) where the agent drives and reviews later.
;;
;; First-class tools:
;;   - read_file                 (collapsed, structure-aware reader)
;;   - clojure_edit              (top-level form replace/insert)
;;   - clojure_edit_replace_sexp (targeted expression replacement)
;;   - paren_repair              (repair unbalanced parens)
;;   - clojure_eval              (REPL evaluation)
;;   - list_nrepl_ports          (discover running nREPL servers)
;;
;; Dirty-file handling (no Claude Code permission setup required):
;;   - :write-file-guard false   -> clojure-mcp never hard-blocks on staleness
;;                                  (safe: the editors above are content-addressed,
;;                                   they reparse the file fresh on every call)
;;   - :mcp-instructions steers ALL Clojure reads AND edits through the clojure
;;     tools, so the host's native Read/Edit never trips its own "modified since
;;     read" check on .clj (and reads stay token-efficient via the collapsed view).

{:mcp-instructions
 "Clojure tooling is available and PREFERRED for all Clojure source files (.clj, .cljs, .cljc, .bb, .edn). For these files, do BOTH your reading AND your editing with the Clojure tools below, rather than your environment's own generic file-reading and file-editing tools (whatever they happen to be named in your harness).

- READ Clojure files with `read_file` instead of a generic file reader. It returns a collapsed, structure-aware view (function signatures only by default, expandable by `name_pattern`/`content_pattern`) that is far more token-efficient than a raw read, and it still supports line ranges via `line_offset`/`limit` and `collapsed: false` when you need the full text.
- EDIT Clojure files with `clojure_edit` (replace/insert a whole top-level form), `clojure_edit_replace_sexp` (replace a targeted expression), and `paren_repair` (fix unbalanced parentheses) instead of a generic text editor or patch tool. These match by code structure rather than exact text, validate parentheses on the way in, and avoid the repeated string-match failures of generic editors.
- EVALUATE and test Clojure/ClojureScript through the persistent nREPL connection tool (`clojure_eval`).

WHY keep every read and edit in these tools: the Clojure edit tools rewrite files on disk. If you interleave them with your environment's own editor on the same file, that editor will often refuse to edit a file that changed on disk since it last read it (forcing a re-read), and a generic reader spends far more tokens dumping whole files. Routing every Clojure read and edit through these tools avoids both problems. Use your environment's own tools for non-Clojure files."

 :disable-tools
 [:grep
  :glob_files
  :bash
  :file_edit
  :file_write
  :scratch_pad
  :dispatch_agent
  :architect
  :code_critique
  :clojure_edit_agent
  :clojure_inspect_project]

 :disable-prompts
 ["create-update-project-summary"
  "plan-and-execute"
  "chat-session-summarize"
  "chat-session-resume"
  "ACT/add-dir"
  "ACT/scratch_pad_load"
  "ACT/scratch_pad_save_as"
  "save_new_prompt"
  "clojure_repl_system_prompt"]

 :disable-resources
 ["PROJECT_SUMMARY.md"
  "README.md"
  "CLAUDE.md"
  "LLM_CODE_STYLE.md"
  "Clojure Project Info"]

 :write-file-guard false}
